Derrick Brown showed up in Week 7, going off with four solos, three assists, and two sacks. Brown is up to three sacks on the season, with all three coming in two of his last three games. Treat him as a DT1/DL3 option for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Buffalo Bills, but count him as more of a plus matchup streamer outside of bye week crunches.

Sweat showed up in Week 7, racking up four solos, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. It was the second sack of the season for Sweat, who has strung together back-to-back games with a strip. Montez has been staying active enough in the solo department to maintain DL3 standing despite the muted sack total. Treat him as such for the plus Week 8 matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

K'Lavon went off against the 'get right' Titans, exploding with two solos, one assist, two sacks, two tackles for loss, one fumble recovery, and one touchdown. Suddenly up to 4.5 sacks on the season, Chaisson has played himself back into the IDP mix. He is more boom or bust than most DL3 options, as he has registered zero solos twice, and just one once in his six games thus far. However, he has emerged as a solid matchup play and should be strongly considered for Week 8, thanks to a plus matchup against Dillon Gabriel and the Cleveland Browns. Ed Oliver returned to action in Week 6, racking up two solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Oliver has tallied two sacks and five tackles for loss in his two contests so far this year, and makes for an excellent DL2/DT1 option when he is healthy. Tap him as a DL2 option as long as he is cooking. Treat him as such for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Carolina Panthers.

A'Shawn was excellent in Week 7, racking up three solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Robinson has quietly tallied one sack in two of his last three games, putting him back in the mix as a deep league DT2 option. Robinson is not much of a DL league option outside of 32-team formats. Look elsewhere for Week 8, despite Robinson's recent strong production.

Scourton notched the first sack of his career, finishing the day with one solo, one assist, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. Scourton has been playing a fantasy-relevant role, but it took him some time to get his first quarterback takedown. He is someone to stash where available in deeper leagues and should now be on radars for those in shallower formats. With that said, Scourton should be left on benches for Week 8 against the Buffalo Bills.

Harrison was excellent in Week 7, reeling off three solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. The Falcons' defensive end is up to a solid 3.5 sacks on the season and is worth a look in deeper leagues. He played 60 percent of the snaps in Week 7, his second-highest mark of the season. Being an odd front defensive end usually limits fantasy upside (Broncos Zach Allen is third in the league with 17 pressures but has just three sacks), but Harrison has recorded at least one sack in three of his last five games, making him an intriguing DL3 option for Week 8, thanks to a plus matchup against a crumbling Miami Dolphins offense.

Elliss showed up in Week 7, racking up four solos, five assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Elliss remains a top-25 play but has been reliant on splash plays so far, making him more of an LB2/3 than a straight LB2. Treat him as such for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Ezeiraku was excellent in Week 7, notching the first sack of his season and finishing the afternoon with three solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. As mentioned, this was Donovan's first sack of the season, but the rookie has managed an impressive 13 pressures on the season (for context, this is more than Rashan Gary (11), Trey Hendrickson (12), and Dorance Armstrong (10)). The Cowboys' edge rusher played 55 percent of the snaps in Week 7, marking the third week in a row he's seen more than 50 percent. The Cowboys like what they have seen from Ezeiraku as he continues to play more snaps than others, like team sack leader James Houston (33 percent). Add Donovan where possible as a bye week filler type who can become a DL2/3 option within a few weeks. Make the add where needed.

Huff was at it again in Week 7, racking up two solos, three assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. Huff is now up to a solid four sacks on the season, with one sack in four of his last six games. Jenkins was excellent in Week 6, reeling off two solos, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and one fumble recovery. Uche was excellent in Week 7, racking up two solos, one assist, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Clowney was excellent in Week 7, racking up one solo, four assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, one fumble recovery, and two passes defended on 39 percent of the snaps. Another one of those occasions may be this week against the Denver Broncos in Week 8

Walker was excellent in Week 6, reeling off four solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended on a season-high 80 percent of the snaps. Zack Baun was excellent in Week 7, racking up six solos and four assists. Baun has tallied five or more solos in five of his seven contests and makes for a strong top-10 option. Treat him as such for what should be an interesting Week 8 tilt against the New York Giants.

Brooks was excellent in Week 7, tallying five solos, four assists, and one tackle for loss. Brooks has recorded a sensational 33 solos in his last four games. Sherwood was excellent in Week 7, racking up seven solos, three assists, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Dodson was excellent in Week 7, racking up five solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Demario was at it again in Week 7, racking up six solos and four assists. The ageless one has registered five or more solos in five of his seven games played, solidifying himself as a locked-in LB2 in the process. Treat him as such for a plus Week 8 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Gray was excellent again in Week 7, tallying seven solos, three assists, and one tackle for loss. Gray has cemented himself as an LB2 option with six or more solos in three of his last four contests. ction, means you should leave him on the bench for Week 8, while we try to get a better handle on how and how often he'll be out there.

Tyson showed up in Week 7, racking up one solo, one assist, one interception, two passes defended, and one touchdown.
